[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test coverage issues**\n\nI’m comparing two packages, `org_assertj.assertj_a` and `org_assertj.assertj_core`, and it seems like one is prioritized over another. If the first test succeeds, the subsequent tests might switch from UsingUnsafeInjection to Override. This could impact existing coverage, particularly for the UsingUnsafeInjection method, which may not be captured anymore. I need to ensure that neither class coverage drops and that dynamic access classes remain well-tested. Keeping track of the overall coverage under these constraints is crucial.\n\n**Refining test execution strategy**\n\nThe developer instructed me to enhance tests so they reach uncovered dynamic-access call sites while ensuring coverage does not decrease. I need to think about isolation here. Previously, tests had no coverage but didn’t cause issues. To cover active tests while keeping the same classloader, I’d need to set UsingUnsafe as unavailable before UsingReflection. Unfortunately, this means the UsingUnsafeInjection path won’t execute in the same JVM. It seems covering UsingUnsafeInjection first isn't really possible either. I need to figure out a better approach!\n\n**Exploring custom class loading**\n\nI’m considering creating a custom `URLClassLoader` to load instrumented AssertJ classes from the Gradle transformed classpath instead of from the original jar. But first, I need to check if there’s an instrumented jar available in the build. I’ll have to search for that to ensure I’m on the right track. It’s important to get this part right to avoid any issues later on!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0cc0101d1dece1b4016a25f9fd6b488193953c9d7a311fdbd6\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJfofEd-qBETErNd_8_iRbuhQUAGW_neFdNw_-suUSKau89DvcwvfU1U-MjLa5yF3Sf7ClkV4lwKaoxIbosyJO08f42n703-c01vA1iwsfHz6NKoHU3QWmXSiyq8J-MPmrmAUmfqLmKtes